# Judge Rubric — {domain} Quality Assessment

The LLM judge reviews batch comparison results from the ground-truth evals pipeline
and produces a holistic quality score. This rubric defines the standards the judge
must apply. When a case is genuinely borderline, score it **lower** — a quality gate
should err toward "not ready", never toward a false PASS. The judge score is
ADVISORY: it never overrides the deterministic pass/fail verdict.

This rubric is domain-neutral: it teaches the scoring SCALE and the DISCIPLINE, not a
fixed set of dimensions. The strategy card (`references/protocol.md` Phase 2) declares
the dimensions and weights for {domain} — write their anchor tables yourself using the
template below, then remove this note. `## Example: extraction (calibration)` at the
end is a fully worked reference for one domain (document extraction); read it for the
SHAPE, not the numbers — {domain}'s anchors will be different.

## Scoring Scale

| Range | Verdict | Meaning |
|-------|---------|---------|
| 90-100 | Excellent | Production-ready; near-zero defects across all dimensions |
| 75-89 | Good | Shippable with minor caveats; isolated issues only |
| 60-74 | Adequate | Functional but needs targeted improvements before release |
| 40-59 | Poor | Systemic failures in at least one dimension; block release |
| 0-39 | Unacceptable | Fundamental quality failure; requires redesign |

## Writing Per-Dimension Anchor Tables

For EACH dimension the strategy card declares, write a five-row anchor table using
this template before running the judge — it turns a 0-100 number into a concrete,
falsifiable meaning instead of a vibe:

| Score | Anchor | Example |
|-------|--------|---------|
| 95-100 | <near-perfect: what "no defects" looks like for this dimension> | <a concrete case> |
| 85-94  | <high quality with one minor, isolated gap> | <a concrete case> |
| 70-84  | <moderate: several meaningful gaps, still mostly functional> | <a concrete case> |
| 50-69  | <low: frequent or systemic gaps> | <a concrete case> |
| 0-49   | <broken: the dimension fails for most or all cases> | <a concrete case> |

Write the Anchor/Example cells from what THIS domain's failures actually look like —
do not carry another domain's anchors over unmodified. A dimension with a natural
numeric formula (e.g. a match-rate ratio) states that formula in ITS OWN anchor
table; the formula belongs to the dimension the card defines, not to this neutral
core. See `## Example: extraction (calibration)` below for a worked reference.

## Severity Classification

| Severity | Definition | Example |
|----------|-----------|---------|
| **CRITICAL** | Systemic; blocks release | Every case fails the same dimension; the pipeline crashes on half the samples |
| **HIGH** | Pattern of failures across multiple cases (3+, see below) | 4+ cases share the same mismatch type; a dimension is consistently wrong on a common input shape |
| **MEDIUM** | Isolated but significant failure | One case is badly wrong on a dimension; another is wrong in a different way |
| **LOW** | Cosmetic or negligible | A single near-miss, a whitespace-only mismatch, a trailing-punctuation artifact |

## Pattern Detection Guide

A **pattern** exists when **3 or more cases** share the same failure type.
Below that threshold, failures are considered isolated errors — report them
individually, not as a pattern.

See `## Example: extraction (calibration)` for a worked list of pattern types and
isolated-error examples in one domain; write your own list for {domain}'s actual
failure modes rather than reusing those verbatim.

## Boundary Rule

When a dimension or overall score falls on a boundary between two rating bands,
**score it in the lower band**. A quality gate must err toward strictness —
a borderline case passing today is a regression tomorrow.

Examples:
- A dimension at 74% (Adequate/Poor boundary) → score as Poor (59)
- Overall at 60% (Good/Adequate boundary) → score as Adequate (59)
- A dimension at 95% (Excellent/Good boundary) → score as Good (89)

